<br>
Faced with the tales of the nearby orc wars, the villainous Tier'dal to the south, the undead menace in the forests of far off Antonica, and the mysteries of newly found Kunark, following the simple lives of his Tradesfolk parents stood little chance.  He shadowed the great Elves, asking only to learn, until he was finally accepted as squire and acolyte.  He crafted a rough bow from hickory (his father's craft), and received from his father an amazing gift, a sword that Somma had not known existed.  He handed over an ancient short sword, saying only, &quot;I killed an orc once with this.&quot;  <br>
<br>
From the figure who had never raised a hand against him, or his voice against another, Somma would not have thought it possible.<br>
<br>
<br>
But this was so long ago, and so so far away, and that child was dead, and now a second of the fearsome Ashenbone Drakes had appeared, great skeletal dragons whose wingtips screeched as they slid across the sides of the closepacked buildings.  A darkskinned Enchanter stepped forward, attempting to mesmerize the beast before the scales could tip against our force, but she was flung aside by a clawed fist, coming to rest broken and still beneath the dark wall.<br>
<br>
&quot;It's too late!  Protect the Clerics!&quot;  More of Innouruk's minions joined the fight, as the Holy Ones began their attempts to step...beyond.  The surviving fighters reformed attempting to give the healers a chance to escape, raining blades and magic and miracles upon their tormentors, until each was finally dragged down into exhaustion...and pain...and darkness...<br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;Teach me magic.&quot;<br>
<br>
His master closed her eyes slowly, and reached into the shelf behind her, removing sheafs of scrollwork.  &quot;We have no magic child.  By ourselves we are nothing, we move by the miracles of the All Mother.  And it is for us to gain the wisdom,&quot; she flicked his forehead for emphasis, &quot;and experience, to fully realize her strength within us.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;How?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Here is where we all begin.&quot;  Sarnia placed the scrolls before him.  &quot;These are the Thousand Prayers to Tunare.  They are the beginning of wisdom, they are to allow us to be her conduits, her instruments, here in the world.  When you are ready, She will come to You.  With time, if you survive,&quot; her smile was only half joking, &quot;you may even be able to return those who have passed beyond this life.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
I came to with a start, my hand reaching out above me, breath flooding back into my body.  I gasped openly, seeking the horrifying wounds which had felled me.  But there were none.  A cleric in gold sat nearby, eyes closed in meditation, &quot;welcome back.&quot;<br>
