<br>
I smiled back.  &quot;Ah, if only it could be true.  Through fifty long trials all I have asked was to be allowed to bear the brunt of the battle.&quot;  I gingerly removed the gauntlet from my left hand, pealing the inner glove from cracked skin, revealing the missing middle finger where an ancient Wyvern claw had crashed through shield and steel and bone.  &quot;But after all this time, I have begun to notice the bleeding.&quot;  I stopped to study the four fingered hand as though it were a specimen behind glass.  &quot;And the things and people I have misplaced along the way.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
Marielle laughed as young Somma kneeled before her, his new banded mail making it much more of a feat than had his old leather pieces.  He knew his courtesy and attention made her uncomfortable, but she tolerated his presence remarkably.  At times, he liked to think, she even welcomed it.<br>
<br>
&quot;M'lady, you are radiant,&quot; And she was.  The young Mage wore a new white robe that seemed to glow from within.  But perhaps that was just her.  She had heard a spell she sought could be found in the library at Ak'Anon, and though he despised the ticking city, he had offered to keep her company on the short trip from Felwithe.<br>
<br>
The trip through the Faydarks was uneventful, this being before the encroachment of the aggressive and powerful Brownie scouts, but upon arriving at the crossroads in the Steamfont Mountains they found the road guard slain.  The unfortunate gnome stared up at the surrounding ridges with unseeing eyes, and the travellers looked as well.  A quick prayer to Tunare was all that could be spared as the two hurried on to the city.  Whatever or whoever had dispatched the guard would have had little trouble with them.<br>
<br>
Upon arrival they reported the incident to the city guards and moved on to the great ticking halls of magic.  They crouched as they moved through the tiny entryways, for hours moving from one unnatural clockwork librarian to the next.  Finally, satisfied that she had been misinformed they escaped the city and the mountains to return to the shining halls of Felwithe.<br>
<br>
The barlass Wela soothed their disappointment with Elven Wine deep into the evening.  They exchanged stories and laughter, and spoke of her entry into the local guildhall, the Elven Elite.  Somma had seen many members crisscrossing Faydwer and had fought alongside several, but he had given little thought to being able to join such a band.<br>
<br>
Mere months later, Somma was also numbered among the ranks of the Elven, invited by his own mentor Sarnia, but Marielle was gone.  She had vanished, probably gone into the East, crossing over from whence none return.  <br>
<br>
Sadly, she would not be the last.<br>
<br>
<br>
The bloodsoaked Ranger snapped her fingers before my face, holding up a broken Drachind leg-tip.  &quot;Hey, we're not done yet.&quot;  She lit the remains and tossed them down into the closest nest.  We heard silk catch fire and then the tell-tale clicking of the beasts, like thousands of the tiny gnome clocks, racing out of control in the darkness.  <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub12.ezboard.com/usommatilmouren.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Somma TilMouren</A> at: 7/11/01 5:40:51 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#BA9F70><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub12.ezboard.com/usommatilmouren.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Somma TilMouren</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Grand Moff</span><br>  Posts: 147<br> <font color=#F5F5DC>(7/13/01 6:35 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/felvenelitefrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=27.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://us.f1.yahoofs.com/users/f326955b/bc/My+Documents/EzBoardSommaPic.jpg?bcAwAK7AxXoXA6n3 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> A Karana Night, pt1</span><hr size=1> In the eastern portion of the Karanas, below the highland falls, there is a hill that the gnolls have claimed as their own.  Whatever magics have been employed there can only be guessed at, but as the sun sets each evening the rotting cadavers of their dead appear as if expelled from the very earth.  The local farmers call them Undead Reavers, and their guards are always on the lookout should the damned creatures wander too close.<br>
<br>
Somma and his childhood friend Leaflaun the druid were hunting the huge crag spiders . . . and the occasional griffawn, a great flying cross between a lion and an eagle, and quite vicious.  Local tailors bought the silk from the spiders and the local residents were always happy to have help with the griffs.<br>
<br>
The pair crept shoulder-deep in the tall Karana grasses, the sharp blades nicking any exposed flesh, as they neared one of the black and red spiders.  Everything was larger here, and more brutish, in the new lands of the humans.  It was as if the gods of the younger races were attempting to make up for other inadequacies through the sheer size of their creations.<br>
<br>
The druid moved quickly away to the right as Somma rose up and loosed a long range arrow at the creature, beckoning it toward him.  It struck home in a hairy flank and the monster shrieked as it raced toward the retreating Paladin, who fired again as he backed away toward the great wooden bridge to North Karana.<br>
<br>
From the spider's left Leaflaun rose from the grass and gestured.  Instantly, fire rose up around it, assaulting their senses with burning flesh.  Roots rose from the earth to entwine its legs and it tried in vain to reach one, then another, of its attackers.  Finally, Somma moved in with axe and shield to finish the contest.<br>
<br>
&quot;I am poisoned.  One moment.&quot;  Somma closed his eyes and mouthed one of the Thousand Prayers, one of cleansing and purification.  He repeated it until he felt the wave of renewal pass through him, certain that the corruption was gone.  &quot;Tunare blesses us.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;What would your teachers say if they saw you fighting as some wild Ranger, with bow and axe, rather than always sticking in your thick head to be pounded on?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;They would say I am cleverer than most, but even so, I could always blame the company I keep.  In any event,&quot; he pulled a broken fang from between two bent banded strips across his tunic.  &quot;I stick my head in quite sufficiently, thank you.  Or at least, just enough to keep my favorite hunting partner in one piece.&quot;<br>
<br>
Leaf extracted the last of the salvagable silk as Somma watched and learned.  Since the first moments they had drawn breath, before they chose their different callings, if one of the boys was around, the other could not be far off.  After a moderately painful learning period, Somma was almost as at home in the trees of his Wood-elf friend as he was on the paved streets of Felwithe.  <br>
<br>
The third member of their ancient club, little Emerelle, had become a true Ranger, joining the Thunderwalker guild.  She had early gone off to seek her fortune, though they still adventured together from time to time.  She could often be seen beneath the branches of Kelethin, helping the young as they learned their ways in the forest.<br>
